{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493392"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:09:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:09:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1311"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1311"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.75,0.02,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1311"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111928"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1311"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1311"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93992"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"682"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2642"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45691"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111928"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man is brought in by ambulance after a head-on motor vehicle accident at 100 km/hr. He was the restrained passenger in the front seat and is orientated to person, place and time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn assessment, GCS is 15, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, pulse rate 120/min, respiratory rate 20/min and SaO2 is 100% on 8L O2/min. He received 50mcg fentanyl IV en route. The patient is in cervical spine precautions. There is no neck pain or neurological symptoms. There is bruising over the region of the seat belt in both the chest and lower abdomen. On auscultation of the chest there is equal air entry to both bases. Abdominal examination shows the previously mentioned seat belt bruising and palpation reveals mild diffuse tenderness, maximal in the lower abdomen, with no guarding.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Give a bolus dose of 1000mL 0.9% NaCl","Perform a FAST scan","Remove cervical spine precautions","Perform erect and supine chest and abdominal X-rays","Perform a full neurological examination"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the trauma patient with tachycardia and concerning mechanism of injury without evidence of significant external haemorrhage, the priority is to exclude concealed cavity bleeding. This patient has tachycardia with a borderline blood pressure (100/60 mmHg is not frankly hypotensive for a young person) and seatbelt sign (bruising over the region of the seatbelt), which is associated with a high risk of blunt abdominal trauma and potential intra-abdominal bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerform a FAST scan\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it can rapidly identify free fluid in the abdomen, which would indicate intra-abdominal bleeding requiring urgent intervention. The Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma (FAST) scan is a bedside ultrasound examination that can be performed quickly during the primary survey to detect free fluid in the pericardial, perihepatic, perisplenic spaces and pelvis. Extended FAST (eFAST) also includes assessment for pneumothorax. This investigation has high sensitivity for detecting significant intra-abdominal bleeding and can guide immediate management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGive a bolus dose of 1000mL 0.9% NaCl\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the most appropriate first step for this patient. While he has tachycardia, his blood pressure is not frankly hypotensive for a young adult, so aggressive fluid resuscitation is not urgently required at this stage. Additionally, in a trauma patient, identifying and stopping the bleeding takes priority. Current trauma management guidelines recommend a more judicious approach to fluid resuscitation until definitive control of bleeding is achieved. Should this patient\u0027s condition deteriorate, blood products would be the most appropriate choice given the likelihood of ongoing bleeding, rather than crystalloid solutions which may dilute clotting factors and worsen coagulopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemove cervical spine precautions\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate at this stage. Despite the patient being alert and denying neck pain, cervical spine injury cannot be excluded based on clinical examination alone in the context of a high-energy mechanism. Cervical spine precautions should be maintained until imaging (typically CT) has excluded significant injury or until a validated clinical decision rule has been applied.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerform erect and supine chest and abdominal X-rays\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate for several reasons. First, the patient should not be placed in an erect position while in cervical spine precautions. Second, plain radiographs have limited sensitivity for detecting intra-abdominal injuries. Third, in the modern trauma setting, FAST scan followed by CT imaging (if indicated) has largely replaced the use of plain radiographs for initial assessment of abdominal trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerform a full neurological examination\u003C/strong\u003E is not the priority in this scenario. While neurological assessment is important in trauma patients, this patient has a GCS of 15, is oriented, and has no neurological symptoms. The immediate concern is the tachycardia and mechanism of injury, which suggest potential concealed hemorrhage. A focused examination has already been performed, and a more detailed neurological examination can be conducted after addressing the more urgent concerns of potential bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Suspect concealed cavity bleeding in the trauma patient with tachycardia and borderline blood pressure with no sign of external haemorrhage.","FAST scan is the most appropriate next step in a haemodynamically unstable trauma patient with suspected intra-abdominal injury.","Seatbelt sign (bruising over the region of the seatbelt) is associated with a high risk of blunt abdominal trauma."],"references":["Nishijima DK, Simel DL, Wisner DH, Holmes JF. Does this adult patient have a blunt intra-abdominal injury? JAMA. 2012 Apr 11;307(14):1517-27.","Nickson C. Abdominal Trauma: Blunt or Penetrating. LITFL. CCC Trauma. Published Dec 7, 2021; revised Dec 21, 2015. Avaialble from: https://litfl.com/abdominal-trauma-blunt-or-penetrating/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93992"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1311"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93992"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-21T17:17:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-22T08:35:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1311"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111928"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":